prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Circumstellar Gas and Dust in Class II YSOs

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our correlator configuration is optimized to encompass the J=2-1 transitions of 12CO, 13CO, and C18O. We include a ~2 GHz continuum baseband centered at 232.5 GHz.

We request an angular resolution of 0.2 arcseconds which corresponds to a physical resolution of ~50AU at the distance of NGC 1333. This resolution will allow us to resolve a large fraction of disks so as to perform more detailed calculations for these targets in pursuit of our science goals (see science justification). The largest angular scale for a source would be ~3 arcseconds corresponding to a disk radius of ~700AU.

We wish to obtain band 6 observations with a C36-5 configuration of the entire Class II YSO population of NGC 1333. Our spectral resolution is set at 0.4 km/s per channel which is more than capable for resolving spectral features from the circumstellar disks. We estimate the faintest sources in our sample to have continuum flux densities of ~2 mJy based on the ~5 mJy faint sources of similar mass and age measured at 1.3mm in Taurus (Andrews et al. 2013) and scaled to the distance of NGC 1333. We estimate a source with ~2 mJy continuum emission would have a 13CO line flux density of ~65 mJy based on the ratio of 13CO to 1.3mm continuum emission measured in detail by Rosenfeld et al. (2013). These estimates represent the faintest targets in our sample and it is likely most the Class II sources will be significantly brighter than this in both continuum and spectral lines. With our configuration, desired sensitivity, and resolution, the ALMA sensitivity calculator measures S/N ratios of 12.5 and 7.2 for the continuum and 13CO spectral line, respectively.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: While a handful of nearby (D < 100 pc), highly evolved (age ~ 10 Myr) bright circumstellar disks remain targets of intense scrutiny with ALMA, little is known in a systematic and unbiased fashion about the significantly more common circumstellar disks in younger, actively star-forming regions. We aim to use ALMA's unparalleled sensitivity to observe all Class II YSOs (young stellar objects) in the nearby (D~240 pc) Perseus star-forming cluster NGC 1333 in a total of ~3 hours . With a high disk fraction of ~85% and an age of 1-2 Myr, very near the median disk lifetime of 2-3 Myr, this cluster represents a unique sample of circumstellar disks that are likely undergoing a phase of rapid disk dispersal. Combined with archival X-ray and near-IR spectroscopy, the proposed 12CO, 13CO, C18O, and continuum ALMA observations of each disk-bearing member of NGC 1333 will provide invaluable evidence pertaining to circumstellar disk gas to dust ratios, physical disk characteristics as a function of spectral type, and disk dispersal timescales via X-ray induced photoevaporation.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
